DiffSenNet: Learning Global Sensitivity Fields for Mechanistic Discovery and Control in Complex Dynamical Systems
Abstract
Understanding and controlling complex dynamical systems remains a fundamental challenge across science and engineering. While recent advances in deep learning have significantly improved predictive capabilities, most existing approaches focus on state forecasting and offer limited insight into the underlying mechanisms governing system behavior. In this work, we introduce DiffSenNet, a novel operator learning framework that shifts the modeling paradigm from state evolution to learning global sensitivity fields.
Instead of directly mapping states to future states, DiffSenNet learns a differentiable representation of how system states respond to variations in intrinsic parameters across both space and time. This formulation enables the model to capture the causal structure underlying dynamical evolution. As a result, the proposed framework not only achieves competitive predictive accuracy but also exhibits strong robustness under parameter extrapolation, rapid adaptation to unseen systems with minimal data, and the ability to identify key parameters and critical temporal windows that govern qualitative system transitions.
We validate DiffSenNet across a diverse set of benchmarks, including chaotic systems, fluid dynamics, heat transfer, and hemodynamic simulations. Experimental results demonstrate that the learned sensitivity fields serve as both predictive operators and interpretable tools for scientific discovery. This work establishes a unified pathway from black-box prediction to mechanism-aware modeling, opening new directions for interpretable and controllable scientific machine learning.

1.Introduction
Understanding the behavior of complex dynamical systems is a central problem in many scientific and engineering domains, including fluid mechanics, climate modeling, biological systems, and material science. These systems are typically governed by nonlinear interactions across space and time, making both prediction and control highly challenging tasks.
In recent years, deep learning–based operator learning methods have shown remarkable success in approximating solution operators of partial differential equations and dynamical systems. Models such as Fourier Neural Operators and DeepONets are capable of learning mappings between function spaces and have significantly improved the efficiency of surrogate modeling. However, despite their predictive power, these approaches largely operate as black-box models. They focus on reproducing trajectories without explicitly modeling the underlying mechanisms that govern system evolution.
This limitation raises several fundamental challenges. First, the lack of interpretability prevents these models from providing insights into which parameters drive system behavior. Second, their generalization ability is often limited, especially when applied to parameter regimes outside the training distribution. Third, adapting these models to new systems typically requires large amounts of data and retraining, which is impractical in many scientific settings.
To address these challenges, we propose a new paradigm centered on learning global sensitivity fields. Instead of learning direct mappings from inputs to outputs, we model how system states change with respect to variations in intrinsic parameters. This sensitivity-based formulation captures the differential structure of the system, enabling a deeper understanding of the relationship between parameters and dynamics.
