2.Results
2.1Framework Overview
The proposed DiffSenNet framework is built upon a fundamental shift in representation: instead of modeling state evolution directly, we learn a global sensitivity field that characterizes how system states respond to parameter variations across space and time.
Formally, the sensitivity field defines a differentiable mapping between system parameters and state variables, capturing the local and global influence of parameters throughout the dynamical process. This field serves as the central representation of the model, encoding both predictive and mechanistic information.
The learning process is implemented using neural networks that approximate the derivatives of system states with respect to parameters. Once the sensitivity field is learned, system trajectories can be reconstructed through numerical integration, enabling forward prediction while maintaining access to parameter influence at every point in space and time.
This design differs fundamentally from conventional approaches. Traditional operator learning methods treat sensitivity as a post hoc analysis, often requiring additional computational steps and providing only local insights. In contrast, DiffSenNet integrates sensitivity directly into the learning process, resulting in a unified framework that supports prediction, extrapolation, adaptation, and discovery.
